bjectivity through literature, and (2) modern literature and history through the study of Turkish literature. The chief concern in this book is not only literature’s response to a particular period in Turkey, but also the role of literature in bearing witness to trauma and drastic political acts of violence—and coming to terms with them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aMen in literature. 0aPolitics in literature. 0aSocial conflict in literature. 0aTurkish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  a20th century, Gender studies, History, Literature, Masculinity, Modernization, Turkey, Women writers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2016z978311078053640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155225376423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155225376/original  a978-3-11-078053-6  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK